queues

Class Jukebox

  • java.lang.Object
    • queues.Jukebox

  • public class Jukebox
extends java.lang.Object
    Manages 3 objects of type Queue of SongEntry - favoritePL, roadTripPL and loungePL favoritePL simulates playlist referred as "favorites" in input file, roadTripPL simulates playlist referred to as "road trip" in input file, loungePL simulates playlist referred to as "lounge" in input file An instance of the class reads a file which includes the user's requests for a the name of a song to be added to a specific playlist. It will then add songs to the three playlists "favorites", "lounge", and "road trip" accordingly. Uses binary search to efficiently look for songs with the specified title
    Author:
    anuva

    • Method Detail

      • fillPlaylists

        void fillPlaylists(java.lang.String requestedFile,
                   SongEntry[] allSongs)
        Reads the test file and then adds songs to one of the three queues. For example, if the file contains line: favorites,title then this method adds the first song with the given title found in allSongs to the favorites playlist Sorts all known songs on song title and uses binary search to efficiently look for songs with the specified title. Growth rate O(log n)
        Parameters:
        requestedFile - String representing path of the input file
        allSongs - Array of SongEntry objects representing all known songs

      • binarySearch

        private int binarySearch(SongEntry[] songs,
                         java.lang.String title,
                         int firstIndex,
                         int lastIndex)
        Binary search algorithm to efficiently search for a title in the sorted array of songs. Running time is logarithmic - O (Log N)
        Parameters:
        songs - Sorted array of songs
        title - String representing title to search for
        firstIndex - integer representing smallest index of the array
        lastIndex - integer representing largest index of the array
        Returns:
        the index of the element in the list that matches the search key if it is contained in the list. Otherwise, it returns -1 (negative)
